  "prompt": "Why are Middle East countries called gulf countries?",
  "response": "The term \"Gulf countries\" refers to the nations located around the Persian Gulf (also known as the Arabian Gulf), which is a shallow sea arm of the Indian Ocean. These countries share coastlines along this body of water. The Gulf countries typically include:\n\n1. Saudi Arabia\n2. United Arab Emirates (UAE)\n3. Bahrain\n4. Qatar\n5. Kuwait\n6. Iraq (partially)\n7. Iran (partially)\n\nThey are called \"Gulf countries\" simply because of their geographic location adjacent to the Persian/Arabian Gulf. The term is primarily used for the Arab states on the western side of the gulf, excluding Iran. These countries are also often referred to as part of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), a political and economic alliance formed in 1981 to promote cooperation among member states.\n\nThe name derives from their proximity to this strategic body of water, which has been historically important for trade, navigation, and more recently, oil production. The gulf region is known for its significant oil reserves and has played a crucial role in global energy markets.",
